            <h4>Meteoroids</h4>
            <div style="padding-left: 1em">
                Meteoroids are chunks of rock and metallic debris that travel through space. Meteoroids tend to range in size from just grains of sand to small pebbles,
                typically, but they have known to be much larger as well. They travel around the sun in a variety of orbits and at varying speeds, with the fastest known
                speeds being around 26 miles per second.  Meteroids are known by many names, but what they technically depends on their current actions.
                [<a href="https://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/HowTheMilkyWayCameToBe-Cherokee.html">REF</a>]
            </div>

            <div style="padding-left: 2em">
                <h5>Meteors</h5>
                When a meteoroid enters Earth's atmosphere it becomes known as a meteor, also commonly known as a shooting star or falling star. The orbital entry is
                what causes the large trail of light behind the meteor. If a cluster of meteors arrive in close vicinity we call them a meteor shower.

                <h5>Fireballs</h5>
                A fireball is a relatively rare phenomenon that is a result of a meteoroid leaving behind a very bright trail of light behind itself. The cause of this is
                usually meteroids that are larger and denser than usual. Fireballs can be so bright that they are occasionally even viewable in broad daylight, although
                this occurence is not too common.

                <h5>Meteorites</h5>
                Rarely, a meteor large enough and dense enough will survive orbital entry and collide with Earth. It is far more common that a meteroid is burned to
                nothingness while attempting to enter Earth's atmosphere but the occasionaly lucky meteroids touch down. We classify the fragment of the meteroid that
                actually makes landfall as a meteorite, they are often highly sought after collectors items as well.
                [<a href="https://i.pinimg.com/originals/69/49/ea/6949eaba58c8ea5fa5b78c2e5bfd43a4.gif">REF</a>]
            </div>
