            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-4">
                <div style="padding-left: 1em">
                    Asteroids come in three broad composition classes, C-type, M-type and S-type. The C-type or chondrite asteroids are among the most common type of asteroids.
                    They consist of clay and silicate rock and are often dark in appearance. Alongside the planets themselves, they are among some of the most ancient objects in
                    the solar system. The M-type or metallic type are composed of nickel and iron. The compositional difference between M-types is a result of how far away from the
                    Sun the asteroid was formed. The S-types fit right in the middle, formed from a mixture of nickel-iron and silicate.
                    [<a href="https://solarsystem.nasa.gov/asteroids-comets-and-meteors/asteroids/in-depth/">REF</a>]
                </div>
