        <h4>Origin of the Name</h4>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-lg-4" style="height: 300px">
                <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/William_Herschel01.jpg/837px-William_Herschel01.jpg" alt="William Herschel" style="height: 100%; width: 100%;" />
            </div>

            <div class="col-lg-8">
                <div style="padding-left: 1em">
                    The name "asteroid" was originally coined by German-British astronomer William Herschel in 1802, however at this time, many scientests referred to them as minor
                    planets. By 1851, there was 15 known asteroids and the naming convention still used today developed with numerals alongside the name of the asteroid.
                    [<a href="https://www.space.com/51-asteroids-formation-discovery-and-exploration.html">REF</a>]
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <h2>Comets</h2>
        <div style="padding-left: 1em">
            <h4>Size</h4>
            <div style="padding-left: 1em">
                Most comets have a nucleus, or central core, of a 6 mile diameter or less. However, the size of a comet varies based on its current proximity to the sun. As a comet nears the
                sun, it begins to vaporize and create a cloud that can expand up to 50,000 miles. More impressive yet is the size of a comets tail which can reach lengths up to 600,000 miles long!
                [<a href="http://coolcosmos.ipac.caltech.edu/ask/182-What-is-the-size-of-a-comet">REF</a>]
            </div>

            <h4>Composition and Structure</h4>
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-lg-5">
                    <div style="padding-left: 1em">
                        Comets are comprised of 4 major components.
                        [<a href="http://spaceguard.rm.iasf.cnr.it/NScience/neo/neo-what/com-compo.html">REF</a>]
                        <ul>
                            <li>Nucleus - this is the relatively stable core of a comet, mostly formed of ice and gas with a small amount of dust and other solids.</li>
                            <li>
                                Coma - this is the dense atmosphere surrounding the nucleus, mostly formed by a cloud of water, dust, carbon dioxide and other natural gases. The coma is
                                formed by the nucleus being heated by the Sun.
                            </li>
                            <li>Dust Tail - this is the most prominent part of the comet, composed of smoke sized dust particles driven off the nucleus from escaping gases.</li>
                            <li>Ion Tail - this tail is composed of plasma and is laced with rays and tracers caused by solar winds.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-lg-7">
                    <img src="https://i.imgur.com/JB2TVTi.png" alt="Comet composition" style="height: 100%; width: 100%;" />
                </div>
            </div>

            <h4>Earth Impact or Near Impact Events</h4>
            <div style="padding-left: 1em">
                Although we have never observed a comet entering Earth's atmosphere, recent evidence suggests that there may have been a comet strike, 28 million years ago in Egypt.
                The resulting blast wave of 3600 degrees fahrenheit melted the sands of the Sahara desert, creating yellow silica glass over 2,300 miles of the desert. The evidence
                was found in a peculiar place, a scarab brooch, made of the silica glass, owned by the famed Pharaoh, Tutankhamen. Within the silica glass, observers noticed a black
                stone in the middle of it, which when put under an isotopic analysis showed that the pebble contained the unique chemical signatures of a comet.
                [<a href="https://www.nationalgeographic.com/news/2013/10/131011-first-comet-impact-egypt-fragment-science-space/">REF</a>]
            </div>

