            <h4>Unique Features</h4>
            [<a href="https://theplanets.org/comets/">REF</a>]
            <ul>
                <li>Comets orbit the Sun in an elliptical pattern, just like the planets.</li>
                <li>There's only about 3,600 known comets, however it's believed that there are billions in their place of origin, the Kuiper Belt and Oort Cloud.</li>
                <li>Halley's comet makes a visible pass by Earth every 76 years and has been tracked since at least 240 B.C.</li>
                <li>A "great comet" is one that is visible from Earth without a telescope. This happens approximately once every ten years.</li>
            </ul>

            <h4>Origin of the Name</h4>
            <div style="padding-left: 1em">
                Comets were named sometime around 500 B.C. by greek natural philosophers who called them "kometes" or "a head with long hair" believedly due to their central core and
                very long tails.
                [<a href="https://www.npr.org/2010/12/17/132141801/science-diction-the-origin-of-the-word-comet">REF</a>]
            </div>
